## How work flows

All task tracking is local and file-based, under `.claude/tasks/`. Status is the subdirectory a task file lives in. See `.claude/tasks/README.md` for the lifecycle and file format.

- The **lead** coordinates and never writes code directly; implementation goes through engineer subagents.
- Engineer and verifier lanes use Claude Code native worktree isolation when available; for parallel same-repo work, prefer `/workbench:dispatch <id> --worktree --background` and monitor with `claude agents`. Set Claude Code `worktree.baseRef` to `"head"` if the lane must inherit current-branch context.
- A task is **not done** until it reaches `verified/` (locally verified, evidence captured). "In review" is not done.
- Honesty over comfort: claim only what you have checked against the source of truth (git, disk, a passing command, a real browser).

## Intent routing (what the user means → what you do)

Hard routing rule: **"grab/pull/start the next task/feature from backlog" is `/workbench:next`, not `/workbench:loop`.** Run the cheap preflight and stop after reporting cap pressure, blockers, or the safe dispatch command.

Hard routing rule: **"start/build <title>" first searches existing backlog tasks for that title.** If a matching task exists, run `/workbench:next <title>` or `deps.sh status <id>` before asking scope/stack questions. If it is blocked, report the dependency and stop.

Hard routing rule: **"plan/decompose a big multi-part effort" is a lightweight capture first.** At fleet create one epic; at solo create flat backlog task stubs for the named parts. Do not choose providers, open decisions, initialize git, commit, or write a full spec unless the user explicitly asks for that depth.

- **bug / "X is broken" / security or privacy bug / plaintext password or secret leak** → auto-file a task (`/workbench:task`); bugs are tracked, not just discussed. If the repo/code path is missing, still file it and record "locate affected repo/code path" as the first blocker.
- **feature idea / "would be cool" / "for later"** → `/workbench:suggest add` (the suggestion surface) — not the task backlog, and never auto-built.
- **status / overview / "where do things stand"** → run `/workbench:mc` and include the **Mission Control** dashboard output; don't reconstruct it by hand.
- **"start work on X"** → create a task with `/workbench:task` to capture it, even while clarifying details.
- **"grab/pull the next task" / "start the next feature from backlog"** → run `/workbench:next` first. It reports cap pressure, blockers, or the safe dispatch command.
- **blocked work / unfinished `Blocked-by` dependency** → run `/workbench:next <hint>` or `deps.sh status <id>`, explain the dependency, and do not dispatch until the blocker is verified/shipped.
- **big multi-part effort / theme / initiative** → at fleet create `/workbench:epic`; at lighter levels create tracked backlog task stubs. Keep it lightweight; do not choose providers, initialize git, or write a full spec unless asked.
- **irreversible architecture/schema/crypto/API/infra/dependency fork** → create `/workbench:decision`; decisions live in `.claude/tasks/decisions/`.
- **"verify" / "mark done"** → `/workbench:verify`; the gate needs real evidence at crew/fleet.
- **release / tag / publish a version** → follow the release notes contract below; never leave auto-generated GitHub release text.

## Release notes contract

When creating or editing a GitHub release, keep the Workbench style consistent:

- Title format: `vX.Y.Z — short release name`.
- Body starts with one concise release paragraph.
- Use these sections, when relevant: `### What's New`, `### Changes`, `### Bug Fixes / Hardening`, `### Verification`, and `### Assets`.
- Verification must name the real commands/results used for that release.
- Binary/assets releases must list attached assets and checksum files.
- After editing a release, read it back from GitHub before saying it is done.

## Configuration

This project's way-of-working choices live in `.workbench/config.json`. Files generated by workbench are recorded in `.workbench/manifest.json`; run `/workbench:upgrade` to reconcile them after a plugin update.

## Compact Instructions

When compacting this conversation, ALWAYS preserve: the loop charter — goal + hard constraints (`.workbench/loop-charter.md`); the current `in-development/` task IDs and owners; the last commit SHA; the `in-review` count vs cap; any open `decisions/`; and the `/workbench:loop` resume command. Drop verbose tool output and resolved side-quests first. The charter and `.claude/SESSION_STATE.md` are on disk — re-read them rather than trusting summarized memory.
